LXIX. There also came into Italy during the battles of the civil war round Bedriacum α north of the Po the ‘new birds’b—for so they are still called—which are like thrushes in appearance and a little smaller than pigeons in size, and which have an agreeable flavour. The Balearic Islands send the porphyrio, an even more splendid bird than the one mentioned above. In those islands the buzzard of the hawk family is also in repute for the table, and the vipio as well-— that is their name for the smaller crane.
